<section xml:id="section-quadratic-forms-terminology">

<title>Terminology and notation</title>

<p><dl>

	<li xml:id="definition-quadratic-forms">
	<title>quadratic form</title>
	<idx>quadratic form</idx>
	<p>
	a multivariable polynomial formula so that each term has degree two;
	that is, if the variables are <m>x_1,x_2,\dotsc,x_n</m>,
	each term in the formula is of the form
	<me> a x_i x_j </me>,
	where each <m>a</m> is an arbitrary constant,
	and where <m>i = j</m> is allowed to produce a true quadratic term
	</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>cross terms (in a quadratic formula)</title>
	<idx>cross terms</idx>
	<p> mixed-variable terms of the form <m> a x_i x_j </m>, with <m>i \neq j</m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>diagonal quadratic form</title>
	<idx><h>quadratic form</h><h>diagonal</h></idx>
	<p> a quadratic form with no cross terms </p>
	</li>

	<li xml:id="definition-quadratic-forms-level-set">
	<title>level set (at level <m>k</m> for a multivariable function <m>f</m>)</title>
	<idx>level set</idx>
	<p>
	the collection of points in <m>\R^n</m> that satisfy <m>f(x_1,x_2,\dotsc,x_n) = k</m>;
	also called a <term>level curve</term> for a piecewise-continuous function in two variables
	or a <term>level surface</term> for a piecewise-continuous function in three variables
	</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>principal axes (for symmetric real matrix <m>A</m>)</title>
	<idx>principal axes</idx>
	<p>
	an orthonormal basis <m>\basisfont{B}</m> for <m>\R^n</m> so that the transition matrix <m>\ucobmtrx{B}{S}</m> orthogonally diagonalizes <m>A</m>
	(where <m>\basisfont{S}</m> is the standard basis)
	</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

</section>
